Triangle $ABC$ has area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot 4 = 6,$ and triangle $ABP$ has area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot BP \cdot \sin \angle BAP.$  We can compute that $\sin \angle BAP = \frac{4}{5},$ so triangle $ABP$ has area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot BP \cdot \frac{4}{5} = \frac{6}{5} BP.$  Therefore, triangle $APB$ has area $\frac{6}{5} BP,$ and triangle $APC$ has area $6 - \frac{6}{5} BP = \frac{24 - 6BP}{5}.$

Triangle $ABC$ has area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot 4 = 6,$ and triangle $ABP'$ has area $\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot BP' \cdot \sin \angle BAP' = \frac{6}{5} BP',$ so triangle $AP'B$ has area $\frac{6}{5} BP',$ and triangle $AP'C$ has area $6 - \frac{6}{5} BP' = \frac{24 - 6BP'}{5}.$

Thus, $P$ is closer to $C$ than it is to either $A$ or $B$ if and only if $BP' > BP.$  Since $P'$ lies inside triangle $ABC$ if and only if $BP' > BP,$ the probability that $P$ is closer to $C$ than it is to either $A$ or $B$ is equal to the ratio of the areas of triangle $ABP'$ and triangle $ABC,$ which is
\[\frac{\frac{1}{2} \cdot 4 \cdot 2.4}{\frac{1}{2} \cdot 3 \cdot 4} = \boxed{\frac{8}{15}}.\]

